0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"markdown-container","children":[["$","h1","h1-0",{"children":"Sector Brief: Aerospace & Space Automation"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Version"}],": 1.0 | ",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Last Updated"}],": 2026-05-07",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Scope"}],": In-orbit manufacturing, autonomous satellite servicing, space debris removal, planetary rovers, and autonomous aviation."]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-0",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"See Also"}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-0",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","a","a-0",{"href":"3.3_Robotics.md","children":"Robotics"}]," — foundational kinematics and manipulation for orbital arms"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","a","a-0",{"href":"3.4_Autonomous_Vehicles.md","children":"Autonomous Vehicles"}]," — autonomous navigation paradigms applicable to aviation"]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","a","a-0",{"href":"../4_The_Horizons/4.1_Research_Frontiers.md","children":"Research Frontiers §1"}]," — safe RL for safety-critical aerospace systems"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-1",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"1. Overview"}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":"Aerospace and space automation represent the most extreme environment for autonomous systems. The massive communication latency between Earth and deep space (ranging from seconds to Mars to hours for the outer solar system), coupled with extreme radiation and thermal conditions, makes teleoperation impractical or impossible. Consequently, space systems require the highest degree of localized, autonomous decision-making."}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":"In 2025–2026, the commercialization of low Earth orbit (LEO) transitioned space automation from experimental rovers to industrial-scale operations, including autonomous satellite life-extension, robotic debris capture, and the first fully automated in-orbit manufacturing facilities."}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-2",{"children":"2. Key Domains of Space Automation"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"children":"2.1 Autonomous Satellite Servicing"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":"Historically, satellites were single-use assets. In 2025/2026, Mission Extension Vehicles (MEVs) and Orbital Servicing Vehicles (OSVs) became standard."}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-1",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Rendezvous and Proximity Operations (RPO)"}],": Autonomous docking with uncooperative targets (satellites not designed to be docked with) using LiDAR and computer vision."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Robotic Refueling and Repair"}],": Using robotic arms equipped with specialized end-effectors to cut thermal blankets, unscrew fuel caps, and refuel aging communications satellites."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Metrics"}],": Docking precision (target: < 2cm error), autonomous capture latency."]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"children":"2.2 Active Debris Removal (ADR)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":"With over 36,000 pieces of orbital debris larger than 10cm tracked in 2026, autonomous cleanup is critical to prevent the Kessler Syndrome."}],"\n",["$","ul","ul-2",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Capture Mechanisms"}],": Autonomous deployment of nets, harpoons, and magnetic capture mechanisms."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"De-orbiting Automation"}],": AI-driven trajectory planning to safely drag debris into the atmosphere to burn up without threatening active constellations."]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-2",{"children":"2.3 In-Orbit Manufacturing"}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"children":"Zero-gravity environments allow for the manufacturing of flawless fiber optics (ZBLAN), perfect protein crystals for pharmaceuticals, and large structures that cannot survive launch stress."}],"\n","$L2","\n","$L3","\n","$L4","\n","$L5","\n","$L6","\n","$L7","\n","$L8","\n","$L9","\n","$La","\n","$Lb","\n","$Lc","\n","$Ld","\n","$Le","\n","$Lf","\n","$L10","\n","$L11","\n","$L12"]}],null,"$L13"]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"sFzo4LKMJghR7e79YRpfU"}
2:["$","ul","ul-3",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Automated Space Factories"}],": Uncrewed capsules functioning as fully automated microgravity laboratories that manufacture high-value goods and return them via autonomous reentry capsules."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"In-Space Assembly"}],": Autonomous robotic arms constructing massive solar arrays or station components in orbit, independent of human operators."]}],"\n"]}]
3:["$","h3","h3-3",{"children":"2.4 Planetary Exploration & Rovers"}]
4:["$","ul","ul-4",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Terrain Relative Navigation (TRN)"}],": Rovers autonomously matching real-time camera feeds against orbital maps to select safe landing zones during the \"seven minutes of terror\" (the period where communication is blocked during atmospheric entry)."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Autonomous Science Targeting"}],": Rovers using AI (e.g., AEGIS framework) to independently identify high-value geological targets and fire observation lasers without waiting for Earth's approval."]}],"\n"]}]
5:["$","h2","h2-3",{"children":"3. Autonomous Aviation (Earth Atmosphere)"}]
6:["$","p","p-6",{"children":"While space represents the extreme, atmospheric aerospace automation saw massive commercial deployments in 2025/2026."}]
7:["$","h3","h3-4",{"children":"3.1 Uncrewed Aerial Systems (UAS) and Drone Delivery"}]
8:["$","ul","ul-5",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"BVLOS (Beyond Visual Line of Sight)"}],": Fully autonomous drone swarms for medical delivery (e.g., Zipline) and package delivery (e.g., Wing) operating without direct human pilots."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Automated Traffic Management (UTM)"}],": AI-driven air traffic control orchestrating thousands of simultaneous drone flights over metropolitan areas, dynamically rerouting around weather and obstacles."]}],"\n"]}]
9:["$","h3","h3-5",{"children":"3.2 Autonomous Flight Decks"}]
a:["$","ul","ul-6",{"children":["\n",["$","li","li-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Single-Pilot Operations (SPO)"}],": Commercial aviation moving toward highly automated flight decks where an AI copilot handles navigation, communications, and emergency procedures, reducing crew requirements."]}],"\n",["$","li","li-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Autonomous Cargo Aircraft"}],": Retrofitted Cessna and ATR aircraft operating autonomously on regional cargo routes, supervised remotely."]}],"\n"]}]
